rmk:
This adult Oriental Reed Warbler was perched on a reed, within a large reed bed at HouTai Wetland 侯台湿地（污水河). There were 3 - 4 individuals in the area taking turns singing.

The sound file is unedited.

Recording made using LG Optimus smartphone.  A single bird singing from atop a small tree near a pond at the Eco-park.  This area is a known breeding location for this species.  Weather was clear skies, temperature around 20°C, light wind from the south.
though not seen but quite confidential.
Recorded within 5m, squacks heard in the background were from egrets in a nesting colony nearby, composed mainly of Cattle Egret and Black-crowned Night-Heron.

Oriental Reed-warbler song.  The bird was singing from a ginkgo tree, along a riverside path.  It then flew into the dense vegetation/reeds closer to the river.  Eventually it took a perch in a tall reed bed, where it continued singing.  There were at least three other reed-warblers singing in the vicinity.

This is an unmodified audio track from a video taken with a Canon EOS 1D-X using its internal microphone. Although it was directed at one Oriental Reed Warbler singing, you can hear many others singing in the surrounding area. Zitting Cisticola were also singing, and Large-billed Crows are nesting nearby. There is also the faint sound of a bittern calling, probably a Eurasian Bittern. There is also very faint traffic noise from a road nearby. The bird was singing from a reed stalk just above the tops of most of the surrounding reeds and just next to a small inlet.
